# Copy to .env.local and fill in. All client vars MUST be prefixed VITE_.
# .env.local is gitignored — never commit real TURN credentials.

# Override the signaling server URL. Leave UNSET for the ngrok/LAN flow, where
# the app talks to the same origin and Vite proxies /signaling to the ws server.
# Set this only if you deploy the signaling server separately, e.g.:
# VITE_SIGNALING_URL=wss://your-signaling-host.example.com

# --- TURN (makes calls work across strict NATs / mobile networks) ---
# The backend now mints short-lived TURN creds itself (backed by a free
# Metered.ca account — set METERED_API_KEY / METERED_DOMAIN on the server,
# see render.yaml) and delivers them to the client over the authenticated WS
# session in the 'joined' message — never a public HTTP route, and never
# baked into this bundle. Nothing needed here for that path.
#
# SECURITY: anything set in a VITE_ var is BAKED INTO THE PUBLIC CLIENT BUNDLE
# and readable by anyone who loads the page. Do NOT ship long-lived static TURN
# credentials here for production — they can be extracted and abused for free
# relay bandwidth. The vars below are only a fallback used when the server has
# no TURN configured; acceptable for local testing, not recommended for prod.
#
# Comma-separated TURN URLs (udp/tcp + TLS variant recommended):
# VITE_TURN_URLS=turn:turn.example.com:3478,turns:turn.example.com:5349
# VITE_TURN_USERNAME=your-username
# VITE_TURN_CREDENTIAL=your-credential
#
# Quick free option for testing — Metered "Open Relay" public TURN:
#   VITE_TURN_URLS=turn:openrelay.metered.ca:80,turn:openrelay.metered.ca:443
#   VITE_TURN_USERNAME=openrelayproject
#   VITE_TURN_CREDENTIAL=openrelayproject
# For production use your own (Cloudflare TURN, a Metered account, or coturn).
